{"title_page": "Ludo Janssens", "text_new": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ludo Janssens\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1942|4|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Antwerp]], Belgium\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 1961\u20131962\n| proteam1       = {{ct|Solo|1961}}\n| proyears2      = 1963\n| proteam2       = {{ct|Libertas|1963}}\n| proyears3      = 1964\u20131965\n| proteam3       = {{ct|Pelforth|1964}}\n| majorwins      = '''[[Classic cycle races|One-day races and Classics]]'''\n:[[Brabantse Pijl]] ([[1962 Brabantse Pijl|1962]])\n:[[Grand Prix de Denain]] (1965)\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Ludo Janssens''' (born on 19 April 1942 in [[Antwerp]]) is a Belgian former [[road cyclist]]. \n\nProfessional from 1961 to 1965, he notably won the [[1962 Brabantse Pijl]], in addition several other larger one day races. \n\nHe also competed in the [[1963 Tour de France]], finishing 39th overall.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/ludo-janssens | title=Ludo Janssens | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;1961\n: 1st [[Druivenkoers-Overijse]]\n: 5th [[1961 Paris\u2013Tours|Paris\u2013Tours]]\n;1962\n: 1st [[1962 Brabantse Pijl|Brabantse Pijl]]\n: 1st [[Nationale Sluitingprijs]]\n: 6th Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a la Comunidad Valenciana]]\n::1st Stage 4\n;1963\n: 2nd [[1963 Omloop Het Volk|Omloop Het Volk]]\n;1964\n: 2nd [[Schaal Sels]]\n: 3rd GP Flandria\n: 5th [[Grand Prix des Nations]]\n: 7th GP de Belgique\n: 9th Overall [[Tour du Nord]]\n;1965\n: 1st [[Grand Prix de Denain]]\n: 8th [[1965 Omloop Het Volk|Omloop Het Volk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|1036}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Janssens, Ludo}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Antwerp]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Belgian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Ludo Janssens\n| image          =\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| full_name      =\n| nickname       =\n| birth_date     = {{bda|1942|4|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Antwerp]], Belgium\n| height         =\n| weight         =\n| currentteam    = Retired\n| discipline     = Road\n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      =\n| amateuryears1  =\n| amateurteam1   =\n| amateuryears2  =\n| amateurteam2   =\n| proyears1      = 1961\u20131962\n| proteam1       = {{ct|Solo|1961}}\n| proyears2      = 1963\n| proteam2       = {{ct|Libertas|1963}}\n| proyears3      = 1964\u20131965\n| proteam3       = {{ct|Pelforth|1964}}\n| majorwins      = '''[[Classic cycle races|One-day races and Classics]]'''\n:[[Brabantse Pijl]] ([[1962 Brabantse Pijl|1962]])\n:[[Grand Prix de Denain]] (1965)\n| medaltemplates =\n| show-medals    =\n}}\n'''Ludo Janssens''' (born 19 April 1942 in [[Antwerp]]) is a Belgian former [[road cyclist]]. Professional from 1961 to 1965, he notably won the [[1962 Brabantse Pijl]], in addition several other larger one day races. He also competed in the [[1963 Tour de France]], finishing 39th overall.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider/ludo-janssens | title=Ludo Janssens | work=ProCyclingStats | accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Major results==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n;1961\n: 1st [[Druivenkoers-Overijse]]\n: 5th [[1961 Paris\u2013Tours|Paris\u2013Tours]]\n;1962\n: 1st [[1962 Brabantse Pijl|Brabantse Pijl]]\n: 1st [[Nationale Sluitingprijs]]\n: 6th Overall [[Vuelta Ciclista a la Comunidad Valenciana]]\n::1st Stage 4\n;1963\n: 2nd [[1963 Omloop Het Volk|Omloop Het Volk]]\n;1964\n: 2nd [[Schaal Sels]]\n: 3rd GP Flandria\n: 5th [[Grand Prix des Nations]]\n: 7th GP de Belgique\n: 9th Overall [[Tour du Nord]]\n;1965\n: 1st [[Grand Prix de Denain]]\n: 8th [[1965 Omloop Het Volk|Omloop Het Volk]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Cycling Archives|1036}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Janssens, Ludo}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Belgian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:Tour de France cyclists]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Antwerp]]\n{{Belgium-cycling-bio-1940s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Karthikdev09", "label": "safe", "comment": "made in user friendly, reader freindly, corrected some grammars", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ludo_Janssens"}
{"title_page": "Mohammad Hasan Mamaqani", "text_new": "'''Mohammad Hasan Mamaqani''' ({{lang-ar|\u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0646\u064a}}; 1822\u2013March 15, 1905) was a leading [[Ijtihad|mujtahid]] of [[Najaf]] in the 19th century. {{Infobox religious biography\n| image               = \n| name                = Mohammad Hasan al-Mamaqani\n| birth_date          = 1822\n| birth_place         = [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|1905|3|15|1822}}\n| death_place         = [[Karbala]], [[Iraq]]\n| children            =[[Bibi Khanum]] \n| office              = \n| religion            = [[Islam]]\n| resting_place       = [[Imam Husayn Shrine]]\n|background=#CEF2E0|honorific prefix=[[Grand Ayatollah]] [[Sheikh]]|creed=[[Shi'a]] [[Twelver]]|native_name=\u0627\u0644\u0634\u064a\u062e \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0645\u0642\u0627\u0646\u064a|relatives=[[Mohammad Hadi al-Milani]] (grandson)}}\n\nHe was born and educated in Najaf . He studied with the highest religious authority of his time, [[Morteza Ansari]]. His daughter and her son became renowned scholars in their own right, [[Bibi Khanum]] (d. 1950) and [[Mohammad Hadi al-Milani]] (d. 1975).\n\nHe is buried under the [[iwan]] of the [[Imam Husayn Shrine|Husayn shrine]].<ref name=\":62\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=ScQ-AQAAIAAJ|title=Mashahir al-Madfunin Fi Karbala|date=2009|publisher=Dar al-Safwa|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=64|language=ar|trans-title=Famous Figures Buried In Karbala}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n*Keddie, Nikki R., Modern Iran: Roots and Results of Revolution, Yale University Press, 2003.\n*[[Moojan Momen|Momen, Moojan]], An Introduction to Shi\u02bbi Islam: The History and Doctrines of Twelver Shi\u02bbism, Yale University Press, 1985.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bibi Khanum]]\n*[[Mohammad Hadi Milani|Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Hadi Milani]]\n*[[Mohammad Kazem Shariatmadari|Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Kazem Shariatmadari]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mamaqani, Mohammad Hasan}}\n[[Category:Iraqi ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n\n<references />{{Iraq-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox president\n| image=\n| honorific-prefix= Ayatollah\n| name = Mohammad Hasan Mamaqani\n| birth_date =    1822\n| birth_place =   [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]\n| death_date = 1905\n| death_place =   [[Najaf]], [[Iraq]]\n| children    =\n| office      =\n| religion    = [[Islam]] ([[Shi'a]] - [[Twelver]])\n}}\n\n'''Mohammad Hasan Mamaqani''' (1822-1905) was a leading mujtahid of Najaf in the 19th century. He was born and educated in Najaf, Iraq, and died there, too. His daughter and her son became great [[Shia Islam|Shiite]] scholars in their own right, [[Bibi Khanum]] (d. 1950) and [[Mohammad Hadi Milani]] (d. 1975).\n \nHe studied with the great marja of his time, [[Ayatollah|grand ayatollah]] [[Morteza Ansari]].\n\n==Further reading==\n*Keddie, Nikki R., Modern Iran: Roots and Results of Revolution, Yale University Press, 2003.\n*[[Moojan Momen|Momen, Moojan]], An Introduction to Shi\u02bbi Islam: The History and Doctrines of Twelver Shi\u02bbism, Yale University Press, 1985.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bibi Khanum]]\n*[[Mohammad Hadi Milani|Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Hadi Milani]]\n*[[Mohammad Kazem Shariatmadari|Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Kazem Shariatmadari]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mamaqani, Mohammad Hasan}}\n[[Category:Iraqi ayatollahs]]\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Brief touch up to page. Aim to fully edit soon.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mohammad_Hasan_Mamaqani"}
{"title_page": "1919 Auckland Rugby League season", "text_new": "The 1919 season of the [[Auckland Rugby League]] was its 11th. It was the first season post [[World War I]] and unsurprisingly it saw a resurgence in playing numbers with 56 teams across the six grades. [[North Shore Albions]] who had previously dropped out of the senior competition again fielded a senior side. As did [[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu]], who had dropped out during the 1917 season.  In addition a new club was formed, namely [[Marist Saints|Marist Old Boys]]. They were composed of old boys of the Marist Brothers\u2019 schools.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Marist Bros. Old Boys/New Club Formed\n| page =9\n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17144\n| date = 1919-04-25\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190425.2.120.2\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> The senior club season commenced on the 3rd of May.\n\n[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] won their third consecutive first grade title, while [[Newton Rangers]] won the Roope Rooster trophy.\n\nAt the end of the season J.B. Cooke stated in a meeting that next season the ball would be rolled into scrums and forwards would have to keep their feet on the ground while the halfback was putting the ball in. These changes were to \u201cbrighten the game\u201d.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Visit of English Team\n| page =4\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17253\n| date = 1919-09-01\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190901.2.9.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-20}}</ref>\n\nThe season was also summarised by the league as well. Forty-nine teams were entered across all grades. Sunnyside won the second grade, Manukau won the third grade, City won the fourth and fifty grades, while Ponsonby won the sixth grade. It was stated that the standard of play in the senior club competition was not as good as it would have been due to the fact that 19 of the best club players from Auckland were away for a large part of the season representing New Zealand in Australia.\n\n===Representative Season===\nThe Auckland representative team was only able to play one inter provincial fixture against Hawkes Bay after matches with Canterbury and Wellington were unable to be scheduled due to the busy New Zealand representative schedule. Likewise Ponsonby were unable to schedule a defense of the Thacker Shield for the same reason. An Auckland Junior team was however able to make a trip out to Napier to play Hawkes Bay and they were victorious by 12 points to 5. Auckland played a match in front of an enormous crowd at the Auckland Domain against the touring Australian side but did not fair any better than the New Zealand national side, going down by 32 points to 8.\n\n===Charitable Efforts and League Funds===\nDuring the war most of the revenue gained by Auckland Rugby League was donated to the war efforts meaning they could not make much progress financially towards developing the game and facilities. In 1919 they once again raised 75 pounds to distribute to local charities nominated by the mayor. They also put on a match at the end of the season to raise money for the St. John Ambulance Brigade. Due to the large crowds at some of the matches, including the match with Australia it was anticipated that the league would gain over 1,000 pounds to establish a fund for obtaining a playing ground. This would of course be [[Carlaw Park]].<ref>{{cite news \n| title =An Eventful Season/Record Gate Receipts\n| page =10\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17291\n| date = 1919-10-15\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19191015.2.116\n| accessdate = 2020-02-10}}</ref>\n\n===Eden Ramblers No More===\nAt the Auckland Rugby League meeting on April 30 it was announced that the Eden Ramblers club had been disbanded. They had formed in 1911 and played in the senior competition from 1911 to 1913 before becoming a lower grade club until this season.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Executive Body\n| page =9\n| publisher =New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17149\n| date = 1919-05-01\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190501.2.121.1\n| accessdate = 2019-12-15}}</ref>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[1918 Auckland Rugby League season|1918]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=11th [[Auckland Rugby League]] season\n|years=1919}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[1920 Auckland Rugby League season|1920]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n==First Grade Championship==\n[[Otahuhu Leopards|Otahuhu's]] first grade team were to only last one round into the season before pulling out. Grafton also struggled to field a team when they lost players to the [[New Zealand rugby league team|New Zealand]] team which was touring [[Australia]]. In round 6 rather than default they were provided with players from the [[City Rovers|City]] and [[Newton Rangers|Newton]] clubs however they too did not survive to the end of the competition.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =North Shore V Grafton\n| page =7 \n| publisher = New Zealand Herald, Volume LVI, Issue 17188 \n| date = 1919-06-16\n| url = https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19190616.2.118.1\n| accessdate = 2019-08-19}}</ref>\n\n[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]] won the championship for the third consecutive season.\n\n===Final Standings===\n{|\n|-\n|\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=175 |Team\n!width=20 abbr=\"Played\" |Pld\n!width=20 abbr=\"Won\" |W\n!width=20 abbr=\"Drawn\" |D\n!width=20 abbr=\"Lost\" |L\n!width=20 abbr=\"For\" |F\n!width=20 abbr=\"Against\" |A\n!width=20 abbr=\"Points\" |Pts\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Ponsonby Ponies|Ponsonby United]]\n|8||6||1||1||99||48||'''13'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[Newton Rangers]]\n|9||6||0||3||132||68||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Maritime\n|8||5||2||1||123||88||'''12'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[City Rovers]]\n|8||5||0||3||96||67||'''10'''\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[North Shore Albions]]\n|10||